																		<td valign="top"
																			style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #333333; font-size: 12px; text-align: justify;"><p>
																				The recent announcement by RBI to reduce rates has
																				got several people expecting a similar easing of
																				rates for home loans.<br /> For the past one year
																				property prices and sales, especially in major
																				metros like Mumbai and Delhi have remained stagnant.
																				High prices of property coupled with high interest
																				rates have ensured that property purchasing is
																				unaffordable for a vast majority of individuals.<br />

																				<br /> With the easing of rates from RBI, a measure
																				to facilitate sufficient liquidity in the market,
																				home buyers have been waiting for the following –
																			</p>

																			<ol>

																				<li>A direct reduction in the home loan rates
																					by banks – thereby inducing demand for property
																					purchasing.</li>

																				<li>New financial products from banks – for
																					e.g. similar to SBI’s housing product where the
																					cost of setting up a new home is also included in
																					the loan sanction amount.</li>

																			</ol>

																			<p>
																				However, while a reduction in rates should translate
																				into higher purchasing power, and lead to an
																				increase in the number of real estate sales, this
																				may not happen due to the likely change in the price
																				of real estate. <br /> <br /> A major factor in
																				the lack of real estate sales has been the current
																				property prices. Over the last year, even when home
																				loan rates have been high the prices of property did
																				not decrease inspite of practically no demand. It is
																				likely that with lower interest rates builders may
																				increase property rates. <br /> <br /> It has been
																				for investors a case of “Heads I win, Tails you
																				lose”<br /> <br /> We have always maintained that
																				property as an asset class given its opaqueness,
																				illiquid nature and high maintenance costs is best
																				purchased for consumption only ie., if you need a
																				house to live in, buy one. Then, prices of property
																				or interest rates would not act as deterrents and
																				you would identify a property that fits your budget.
																				But, for people looking at investing surplus cash in
																				property – can’t say for now when the time will be
																				right.
																			</p></td>

